                    />

            
    
<figcaption class="attribution">
        <span class="attribution__caption">Angelica Zavala with her two daughters before school</span>
    
        <span class="attribution__credit">
        <span class="a11y">Credit: </span>
        Ash Ponders, special to ProPublica
    </span>
    
    
    </figcaption>

</figure>

        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="8.0">Yet when it comes to lower-income families actually choosing to use vouchers here in <a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2024/04/03/arizona-school-choice-thriving/">the nation’s school choice capital</a>, the numbers tell a very different story. A ProPublica analysis of Arizona Department of Education data for Maricopa County, where Phoenix is located, reveals that the poorer the ZIP code, the less often vouchers are being used. The richer, the more.</p>
        
    
                    
            
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="10.0">In one West Phoenix ZIP code where the median household income is $46,700 a year, for example, ProPublica estimates that only a single voucher is being used per 100 school-age children. There are about 12,000 kids in this ZIP code, with only 150 receiving vouchers.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="11.0">Conversely, in a Paradise Valley ZIP code with a median household income of $173,000, there are an estimated 28 vouchers being used per 100 school-age children.</p>
        
    
                    

